Websocket - Wikipedia Edits¶

1. Introduction¶

Attempt to pull data through a web socket and then preprocess + analyse. The main bulk of analysis will focus on whether we can trust what we read on wikipedia, and what that suggests about what we read online. I will do this through examining both the edits themselves and the editors making the editions.

def countplot(var, data):
    total = len(data[var])
    g = sns.countplot(x = var, data = data,order=data[var].value_counts().iloc[:20].index)
    if len(data[var].unique()) <= 10:
        for p in g.patches:
            percentage = '{:.1f}%'.format(100 * p.get_height()/total)
            x = p.get_x() + p.get_width() / 2 - 0.05
            y = p.get_y() + p.get_height()
            g.annotate(percentage, (x, y), size = 12)
    plt.xlabel('Categories')
    plt.ylabel('Count')
    plt.title(f'countplot: {var}')
    if len(data[var].unique()) > 5:
        plt.xticks(rotation=90)
    plt.show()

def outlier_box(df,col):
    g = sns.boxplot(data =  df[col], orient = 'h', palette = 'Set3')
    g.set_title('Detecting Outliers')
    plt.ylabel(col)
    plt.show()   
    
def geo_plot(dat, h = None,t = 'Where are wikipedia edits being made?', s = 100):
    ax = world_map.plot(color = 'black', edgecolor = 'white')
    ax.set_facecolor('xkcd:white')
    g = sns.scatterplot(x = 'geo_ip.longitude',
                        y = 'geo_ip.latitude',
                        data = dat, hue = h,
                       s = s,
                       linewidth = 0, ax = ax)
    g.set_title(t)
    g.tick_params(bottom = False, left = False)
    g.axis('off')
    g.set(xticklabels=[])
    g.set(yticklabels=[])
    plt.show()
    
def plot_hist(var, lab1,lab2, min_size = -1000, max_size = 1000):
    plot_data = df[(df['change_size'] != 0)]
    plot_data['change_size'] = np.clip(plot_data['change_size'],a_min = min_size, a_max = max_size)
    plt.hist(plot_data[plot_data[var] == True]['change_size'], bins = 30, alpha = 0.4, label = lab1)
    plt.hist(plot_data[plot_data[var] == False]['change_size'], bins = 30, alpha = 0.4, label = lab2)
    plt.xlabel('Change Size')
    plt.ylabel('Number of edits', size = 12)
    plt.legend(loc = 'upper left')
    plt.show()
    
def create_wordcloud():
    wordcloud = WordCloud(stopwords = stopwords, background_color = 'white',
             width = 800, height = 400).generate(' '.join(text_data))
    plt.axis('off')
    plt.figure(figsize = (40,20))
    plt.tight_layout(pad = 0)
    plt.imshow(wordcloud, interpolation = 'bilinear')
    plt.show()

We can put this together by adding records to a df provided we can read them. Stream data for an hour, add edit time and then save:

In [6]:
df = pd.DataFrame()   

ws = create_connection("ws://wikimon.hatnote.com:9000")

timeout = time.time() + 3600*1
while time.time() < timeout:
    js = json.loads(ws.recv())
    js['edit_time'] = datetime.datetime.now()
    if isinstance(js, dict):
        df = pd.concat([df, pd.json_normalize(js)])
    else:
        assert "Unknown Data"
    time.sleep(1)
df.to_csv('websocket_stream.csv', index = False)
print('Data Saved')

Data Saved

6. Change Size¶

Next, I want to explore change size as that seems like an important feature. Generally, we would expect large changes to be is_minor=False, not made by bots and made by users with names (as they are more likely to be trusted editors).

I think we can conclude that generally the information is reliable because larger changes are normally set to major, they are made by people with usernames and are patrolled.

In [24]:
# Time zones
my_func = TimezoneFinder().timezone_at

# Define new df of geo features only
tz_df = df[~df['geo_ip.latitude'].isnull()]

# Add timezone for each location
tz_df['timezone'] = tz_df.apply(lambda x : my_func(lat = x[ 'geo_ip.latitude'], 
                                             lng = x['geo_ip.longitude']), axis = 1)

# Convert edit time to datetime format
tz_df['edit_time'] = pd.to_datetime(tz_df['edit_time'])

# Convert time to local using timezone
tz_df['local_edit_time'] = (pd.to_datetime(tz_df.groupby('timezone')['edit_time']\
                            .transform(lambda x: x.dt.tz_localize('UTC').dt.tz_convert(x.name))\
                            .astype(str).str[:-6]))

# Take hour of the day from new time
tz_df['hour'] = tz_df['local_edit_time'].astype(str).str.slice(11,13).astype(int)

# View
tz_df.iloc[:,19:].head()

Unfortunately, since the data was taken from a single hour of the day, the all this means is that edits in Australia were made around midnight, West America the early hours and East America, Europe/Asia during the day. This could explain why we are generally seeing more in Europe/Asia. We can confirm using a countplot of the timezone:

In [26]:
rcParams['figure.figsize'] = 8,4
countplot(data = tz_df, var = 'timezone')

We could tentatively conclude that edits are generally made at what we might consider a reasonable time during the day and therefore we can more reliably trust the information but it could also simply be that edits are generally made by people from more central time zones (there may also be more people). Without 24hrs of data we can't tell.

8. Text Features¶

Finally, I want to explore whether we can learn anything from the titles of the articles being edited. Firstly, take the title column and do some basic preprocessing:

In [27]:
# Take page titles
text_data = " ".join(title for title in df.page_title.astype(str))

# Replace : with space
text_data = text_data.replace(':',' ')

# Remove punctuation
text_data = text_data.translate(str.maketrans('','',string.punctuation))

# Lower case
text_data = text_data.lower()

# Tokenise
text_data = nltk.word_tokenize(text_data)

# Define stopwords
stopwords = set(STOPWORDS)

# Add some custom stopwords
stopwords.update(['wikipedia','user','edit','special','category','talk','draft',
                 'logdelete','logabusefilter','lognewusers', 'list','file','logmove','wikiproject'])

# View first 5 words
text_data[0:5]
Out[27]:
['jos', 'abad', 'santos', '2021', 'wimbledon']

Now view on a wordcloud:

In [28]:

Again, most of what I can see looks reasonable as the pages which are being edited seem like current or live events in progress.

As a final conclusion, based on what we can infer from the data, the information on Wikipedia is generally accurate. This is good, since Wikipedia is an encyclopedia and is considered reliably sourced information. If you know where to look, information on the internet is accurate.
